# Single-Tube Opposing-Flow Rotary Valve Engine
## with Thermal Self-Regulation and Gear-Ratio Stroke Switching

**Date conceived:** Prior to 2026-07-09 (physical prototype built and tested)
**Author:** Bryan Robert Horsfield
**Status:** Prior art declaration — working prototype exists

---

## Core Concept

A rotary valve engine where a single rotating tube replaces all 
conventional valve train components. Intake and exhaust gases travel 
through the centre of the same tube in opposing directions, timed by 
the rotational position of ports cut into the tube walls.

One moving part in the head. No poppet valves, no springs, no camshaft,
no rockers.

---

## The Tube

A single hollow tube rotates on the combustion axis. Ports are cut into 
the sides of the tube at calculated angles. As the tube rotates:

- Port alignment with the intake passage = intake open
- Port alignment with the exhaust passage = exhaust open
- No alignment = both closed (compression/power stroke)

Intake and exhaust share the same geometric path through the centre of 
the tube — what determines whether gas enters or exits is purely the 
rotational timing, not separate physical pathways.

---

## The Opposing Flow Thermal Solution

The fundamental problem with rotary valves has always been sealing under 
heat. Conventional solutions attempt to solve this with exotic materials 
or tight tolerances — both expensive and failure-prone.

This design solves it thermodynamically:

- Exhaust gas exits through the tube centre — heats the tube
- Intake charge enters through the same path — cools the tube
- The tube reaches thermal equilibrium between intake and exhaust temperatures
- This equilibrium is predictable and stable — **thermal stasis**

Because the tube never reaches full exhaust temperature, thermal 
expansion is:
- Lower in magnitude than conventional exhaust valve exposure
- Predictable and consistent
- Designable — tolerances can be set around a known thermal state

The seal works because expansion is controlled by the physics of the 
design, not fought with materials engineering.

---

## Two/Four Stroke Switching by Gear Ratio

The rotary valve tube is gear-driven from the crankshaft.

- **Two stroke:** tube driven at 1:1 ratio with crank — ports open every 
  revolution
- **Four stroke:** tube driven at 1:2 ratio — ports open every second 
  revolution

No mechanical changes to the engine. No redesign. Same tube, same ports,
same geometry. Stroke cycle changed entirely by the gear ratio between 
crank and valve tube.

This is an inherent property of the gear-driven rotary valve architecture
— not a feature requiring additional engineering.

