## Prototype

A working single-cylinder prototype has been built and tested:

- Construction: transparent acrylic (for visual verification of internal 
  operation)
- Cylinder and piston: sourced from nitro RC engine
- Valve drive: RC helicopter gear components
- Bearings: 3mm OD miniature ball bearings throughout
- Flywheel: counterbalanced clear acrylic disc
- Power source: fishtank air pump
- Operating speed: approximately 3500 RPM confirmed

The prototype demonstrates the opposing-flow thermal regulation and 
single-tube valve timing in operation. Visual construction allows 
direct observation of all moving components during operation.

A three-cylinder radial variant was also built (subsequently 
disassembled) where the crankshaft itself served as the rotary valve 
tube — eliminating the gear drive entirely and making valve timing 
geometrically locked to piston position (cannot go out of time).

---

## Advantages Over Conventional Poppet Valve Train

| Property | Poppet Valve | This System |
|----------|-------------|-------------|
| Moving parts in head | Multiple (valves, springs, rockers, cam) | One (rotating tube) |
| Thermal sealing challenge | Managed by materials | Solved by opposing flow |
| Stroke switching | Requires mechanical changes | Gear ratio only |
| Failure modes | Spring failure, burnt valves, timing | Single rotating component |
| Manufacturing complexity | High | Low |
| Transparency/serviceability | Low | High |

---

## The Radial Variant — Crank as Valve

In the three-cylinder radial configuration:

- The crankshaft IS the valve tube
- Ports cut into the crank at calculated positions serve all three cylinders
- Valve timing is geometrically impossible to get wrong — crank position 
  IS valve position
- Eliminates gear drive entirely
- Further reduces moving parts

This variant was physically constructed from RC helicopter components 
and transparent acrylic using hand tools. Not completed to running 
condition due to manufacturing precision limits of hand tools, but 
mechanically correct in assembly.

